qas.question: What slavic word denotes "people who speak the same language?"
Who considered *Slověninъ do be a derivation from slovo?
Who came up with the Slavic autonym?
What word did Roman Jakobson use to call Slavics foreign people?
What word did Jackobson use to mean mute?

context: The Slavic autonym *<b4_0>Slověninъ<b4_0/> is usually considered (e.g. by <a2_0><b3_0>Roman Jakobson<b3_0/><a2_0/>) a derivation from <a0_0>slovo<a0_0/> "word", originally denoting "people who speak (the same language)," i.e. people who understand each other, in contrast to the Slavic word denoting "foreign people" – <a1_0><b5_0>němci<b5_0/><a1_0/>, meaning "mumbling, murmuring people" (from Slavic *<b6_0>němъ<b6_0/> – "mumbling, mute").
